161932/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/02/13/relative-of-covid-19-patient-becomes-malaysias-19th-case-says-health-minist/1837243|archive-date=23 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 1 February, she went to Kuala Lumpur Hospital for treatment because of a slight fever. The doctor allowed her to go home to rest after prescribing the medicine but ordered her and her group to stay indoors and isolate. The county health officials continued to monitor the woman and found that her condition persisted until 5 February, she was referred again to Kuala Lumpur Hospital and later diagnosed with the virus on the same day.<ref name=\"13th and 14th infected patient\"/> She was discharged from the hospital on 24 February.<ref name=\"two Chinese nationals COVID-19 patient discharged\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/02/568613/two-more-covid-19-patients-malaysia-recover-discharged|title=Two more Covid-19 patients in Malaysia recover, discharged|agency=Bernama|via=New Straits Times|date=24 February 2020|accessdate=26 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226004017/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/02/568613/two-more-covid-19-patients-malaysia-recover-discharged|archive-date=26 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| Discharged\n|-\n| 15\n|\n| 6 February 2020\n| 16 February 2020\n| 59\n| {{CHN}}\n| A Chinese female national from Wuhan, arrived in Singapore with her husband, son and daughter-in-law on 17 January and passed through Johor Bahru on 21 January <!-- It is unknown whether it was the Woodlands or Tuas Checkpoint Entry --> to Malaysia. She developed fever on 26 January but did not go to any medical centre for treatment. She only took [[antipyretic]] herself and stayed indoors. She had planned to fly with her son and daughter-in-law from Johor Bahru to Guangzhou on 4 February but was not accompanied by her husband due to physical discomfort. On 5 February, the management of her residence reported her condition t