{"title_page": "Gulf Bridge International", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name = Gulf Bridge International\n| logo = NewGBI-logo(2).jpg\n| logo_alt = Gulf Bridge International (GBI) Logo\n| logo_size = 250px\n| caption = \n| type = Private\n| traded_as = \n| genre = <!-- Only used with media and publishing companies -->\n| fate = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| foundation = {{Start date|2008}}\n| founder = \n| defunct = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| location_city = [[Doha]]\n| location_country = [[Qatar]]\n| location = Level 2, [[Qatar Science & Technology Park]] Tech 1\n| area_served = Middle East, Europe & Asia\n| key_people = {{unbulleted list\n | Abdulla Al Rwaili  {{small|([[Executive Director and Managing Director]])}}\n}}\n{{unbulleted list\n | Cengiz Oztelcan {{small|([[Chief Executive Officer]])}}\n}}\n| industry = [[Telecommunication]]s\n| products = \n| services = Submarine Cable Operator\n| revenue = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income = \n| aum = <!-- Only used with financial services companies -->\n| assets = \n| equity = \n| owner = \n| num_employees = \n| parent = \n| divisions = \n| subsid = \n| homepage = {{url|http://www.gbiinc.com/}}\n| footnotes = \n| intl = \n}}\n'''Gulf Bridge International''' (GBI) is the Middle East\u2019s first privately owned [[submarine communications cable|submarine cable]] system linking the countries bordering the [[Persian Gulf]] on a self-healing ring to each other and onwards to Europe, Africa and Asia.<ref>{{cite web|first=Stephanie|last=Hancock|date = 6 June 2011|title = Superfast broadband may help make Qatar new tech hub\n|publisher = BBC Business News|url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-13667229|accessdate = 8 June 2011}}</ref> Its main headquarters are located at the [[Qatar Science & Technology Park]] in [[Doha]], [[Qatar]].\n\n==History==\nIncorporated in December 2008, GBI started production and deployment of the \u2018Gulf Ring\u2019<ref>{{cite web|date = 24 December 2010|title = Gulf Bridge International and SubCom commence marine operations for GBI Cable System|publisher = TeleTimes International|url = http://teletimesinternational.com/middleeast/1433/gulf-bridge-international-and-subcom-commence-marine-operations-for-gbi-cable-system|accessdate = 8 June 2011|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120324184141/http://teletimesinternational.com/middleeast/1433/gulf-bridge-international-and-subcom-commence-marine-operations-for-gbi-cable-system|archive-date = 24 March 2012|url-status = dead}}</ref>&nbsp;\u2013 a \"high speed, subsea cable system\" connecting the countries overlooking on Persian Gulf together and integrated into the larger GBI Cable System (GBICS) which has onward East and West links to Europe, Africa and Asia.<ref>{{cite press release|date = 23 September 2010|title = GBI and Interoute announce network extension partnership|publisher = Arabian Business Report|url = http://www.arabianbusiness.com/press-release/?pressReleaseId=42702|accessdate = 8 June 2011}}</ref> The high capacity demand from the Middle East and lack of diversity/resilience (as witnessed by the cable outages of 2008.<ref>{{cite web|date = 19 December 2008|title = Damaged cables cause internet outages for millions|publisher = The Guardian UK|url = https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2008/dec/19/undersea-cables-cut|accessdate = 8 June 2011}}</ref>) were large driving factors for the establishment of GBI.\n\n==Market Growth==\nBetween 2005 and 2010 the Middle East was the fastest growing region globally in terms of demand for bandwidth and capacity usage. This demand is forecast to double every three years over the course of the next decade, being driven by several factors:\n* Opening up of the regional telecom markets to competition which has stimulated an unprecedented increase in the use of mobile and broadband internet services.\n* Government initiatives around the Persian Gulf to lessen dependence on carbon based industries and diversify their investments to include other sectors, have increased the demand for superior levels of international connectivity from sectors such as Finance and Media.<ref>{{cite press release|date = 31 October 2010|title = Non-oil growth in the GCC forecasted to grow 5.1% in the next ten years|publisher = Qatar Financial Center|url = http://www.qfc.com.qa/en-us/Media-center/Media-news-detail.aspx?sNewsID=7242454d-a71a-45d4-9cf1-68e315583025|accessdate = 8 June 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Present==\nSince its establishment, the business has been validated, both by the participation of new regional investors and telecom operators looking for a new business model; and the infrastructure to enable them to provide new applications and services.<ref>{{cite press release|date = 25 May 2011|title = Gulf Bridge International (GBI) Selects Centina Systems as Their End-to-End OSS Solution Provider for Their Sub-Sea Broadband Carrier Network to Provide Outstanding Customer Service|publisher = Yahoo Finance|url = https://finance.yahoo.com/news/Gulf-Bridge-International-GBI-iw-2449996314.html?x=0&.v=1|accessdate = 8 June 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|date = 28 November 2011|title = Subsea cable network to upgrade Iraq links|publisher = Reuters|url = https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/11/28/subsea-qatar-idUSL5E7MS30H20111128| work=Reuters|accessdate = 28 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nGBI currently has presence in:\n* [[Qatar]]<ref>{{cite press release|date = 20 March 2011|title = Gulf Bridge International and Vodafone Qatar Announce Successful Cable Landing|publisher = Business Wire|url = http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20110320005036/en/Gulf-Bridge-International-Vodafone-Qatar-Announce-Successful|accessdate = 8 June 2011}}</ref>\n* [[United Arab Emirates]]<ref>{{cite press release| title = Gulf Bridge International completes its first cable landing in UAE| date = 15 March 2011| url = https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/03/14/idUS228205+14-Mar-2011+BW20110314| work=Reuters}}</ref> - Dubai and Fujairah\n* [[Iran]]<ref>{{cite web|date = 27 April 2010|title = TIC, Gulf Bridge International Agree to land GBI's submarine cable in Iran|publisher = Al Bawaba|url = http://www1.albawaba.com/business/tic-gulf-bridge-international-agree-land-gbis-submarine-cable-iran|accessdate = 8 June 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Iraq]] - This was a major first by GBI, as it placed the first ever submarine cable connecting Iraq to the world.<ref>\n{{cite web\n|date = 17 January 2012\n|title = GBI lands first subsea cable in Iraq \n|publisher = Trade Arabia\n|url = http://www.tradearabia.com/news/IT_211116.html\n|accessdate = 31 January 2012\n}}</ref>\n\n* [[Kuwait]]<ref>{{cite web\n|year = 2010\n|title = Kuwait National Technology Enterprises Ongoing Projects\n|publisher = Kuwait National Technology Enterprises\n|url = http://www.ntec.com.kw/Client/content.aspx\n|accessdate = 8 June 2011\n}}{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=June 2011}}\n* [[Bahrain]]<ref>{{cite press release\n|date = 7 March 2010\n|title = Gulf Bridge International (GBI) signs with to Batelco to Land GBI\u2019s Sub-Sea Cable System in the Kingdom of Bahrain\n|publisher = Bloomberg\n|url = https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=conewsstory&tkr=BATELCO:BI&sid=aYuIAjqoKDIY\n|accessdate = 8 June 2011\n}}</ref>\n* [[Oman]]<ref>\n{{cite press release\n| date = 10 May 2010\n| title = Gulf Bridge International, Omantel sign agreement to land GBI\u2019s sub-sea cable system in Oman\n| publisher = Submarine Telecoms Forum\n| url = http://www.subtelforum.com/articles/?p=2416\n| accessdate = 8 June 2011\n}}</ref>\n\n* [[Saudi Arabia]]<ref>\n{{cite press release\n| title = Gulf Bridge International (GBI) and the Saudi Telecom Company (STC) Announce the Landing of GBI's Submarine Cable in the East Coast of the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia.\n| date = 28 February 2010\n| url = https://www.reuters.com/article/2010/02/28/idUS56319+28-Feb-2010+BW20100228\n| work=Reuters\n}}</ref>\n* [[Italy]]<ref>\n{{cite press release\n|date = 15 November 2010\n|title = GBI and Tinet Partner Together to Extend GBI's Middle East and Asian Connectivity Into Europe and to Offer Tinet's Global IP and Ethernet Services in the Gulf Area\n|publisher = Market Wire\n|url = http://www.marketwire.com/press-release/gbi-tinet-partner-together-extend-gbis-middle-east-asian-connectivity-into-europe-offer-1353021.htm\n|accessdate = 8 June 2011\n}}</ref>- Milan\n* [[India]]<ref>\n{{cite web\n|date = 25 May 2010\n|title = Sify Technologies in pact with Gulf Bridge International\n|publisher = The Times Of India\n|url = http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2010-05-25/news/27609820_1_gulf-bridge-international-managing-director-raju-vegesna-enterprise-and-consumer-internet\n|accessdate = 8 June 2011\n}}</ref>-[[Mumbai]] and [[Chennai]]\n*[[Singapore]]\n*[[London|England-London]]\n*[[Marseille|France -Marseille]] and Paris\n*Germany-[[Frankfurt]]\n*Netherlands- [[Amsterdam]]\n\n==Products==\nGBI products include a full suite of wholesale transmission, IP capacity options, and Enterprise Services including:\n\nWDM and Transmission capacity services:\n\n* [[Synchronous Digital Hierarchy]];  IPLC Products  STM1 to STM64\n\n* [[Wavelength-division multiplexing]] ; Wavelengths at 10 and 100 [[Gbit/s]]\n\n* [[Ethernet]] over SDH;  EPL Products from 0.1 to 10 Gbit/s\t\n\nPacket-based IP/MPLS services:\n\n* [[Internet transit|IP Transit]]; At Neutral [[Gulf Cooperation Council|GCC]] Datacenters, [[Europe]] and [[Singapore]] from 0.1 to 10 Gbit/s\t\n* Content-Transit ; To specific desired content from 1 to 10 Gbit/s\n\n* [[Ethernet]] Over [[Multiprotocol Label Switching|MPLS]]; Backbone services across Neutral Datacenters in GCC , Europe and Singapore from 0.1 to 10 Gbit/s\t\n\nManaged Connectivity Services:\n\n* Global [[Virtual private network|VPNs]]; From 1[[Mbps]] global corporate [[Wide area network|WAN]] Layer 2 and 3 services over [[Multiprotocol Label Switching|MPLS]] or [[SD-WAN]] technologies\n* Cloud-Connect; From 10[[Mbps]] global Private and Public cloud connectivity ([[Amazon Web Services|AWS]], [[Microsoft Azure|Azure]], Oracle, [[SAP SE|SAP]], etc.) over [[Multiprotocol Label Switching|MPLS]] or [[SD-WAN]] technologies\n*IX-Connect; From 1[[Data-rate units|Gbps]] to 10[[Data-rate units|Gbps]] for remote peering at desired Internet Exchange worldwide\n*Content-Connect; From 1[[Data-rate units|Gbps]] to 100[[Data-rate units|Gbps]] to major contents in the [[Gulf Cooperation Council|GCC]] and [[Europe]].\n*Managed Hosting; For Media and Gaming industries consisting of [[Infrastructure as a service|IaaS]] or Colocation and connectivity services at [[Gulf Cooperation Council|GCC]] Neutral Datacenters.\n\nProfessional Services:\n\n*[[Cloud computing|Cloud]] Provisioning Services\n\n*[[Firewall (computing)|Firewall]] Assurance Management Services\n* Security and Network Consulting Services\n\n==Awards==\n* 2012 Best Niche/New Player - Capacity Europe<ref>\n{{cite web\n|date = 10 February 2013\n|title = Capacity Awards 2012\n|publisher = Capacity Magazine\n|url = http://www.capacitymagazine.com/Capacity-Awards.html\n|accessdate = 10 February 2013\n}}</ref>\n* 2012 Best Technology Investment - CommsMEA<ref>\n{{cite web\n|date = 5 December 2012\n|title = MEA telcos lauded at CommsMEA Awards\n|publisher = CommsMEA \n|url = http://www.commsmea.com/12855-mea-telcos-lauded-at-commsmea-awards/#.UReTJGdFPYM\n|accessdate = 10 February 2013\n}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.gbiinc.com/}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2011}}\n\n[[Category:Submarine communications cables in the Indian Ocean]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 2008]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name = Gulf Bridge International\n| logo = NewGBI-logo(2).jpg\n| logo_alt = Gulf Bridge International (GBI) Logo\n| logo_size = 250px\n| caption = \n| type = Private\n| traded_as = \n| genre = <!-- Only used with media and publishing companies -->\n| fate = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| foundation = {{Start date|2008}}\n| founder = \n| defunct = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| location_city = [[Doha]]\n| location_country = [[Qatar]]\n| location = Level 2, [[Qatar Science & Technology Park]] Tech 1\n| area_served = Middle East, Europe & Asia\n| key_people = {{unbulleted list\n | Abdulla Al Rwaili  {{small|([[Executive Director and Managing Director]])}}\n}}\n{{unbulleted list\n | Cengiz Oztelcan {{small|([[Chief Executive Officer]])}}\n}}\n| industry = [[Telecommunication]]s\n| products = \n| services = Submarine Cable Operator\n| revenue = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income = \n| aum = <!-- Only used with financial services companies -->\n| assets = \n| equity = \n| owner = \n| num_employees = \n| parent = \n| divisions = \n| subsid = \n| homepage = {{url|http://www.gbiinc.com/}}\n| footnotes = \n| intl = \n}}\n'''Gulf Bridge International''' (GBI) is the Middle East\u2019s first privately owned [[submarine communications cable|submarine cable]] system linking the countries bordering the [[Persian Gulf]] on a self-healing ring to each other and onwards to Europe, Africa and Asia.<ref>{{cite web|first=Stephanie|last=Hancock|date = 6 June 2011|title = Superfast broadband may help make Qatar new tech hub\n|publisher = BBC Business News|url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-13667229|accessdate = 8 June 2011}}</ref> Its main headquarters are located at the [[Qatar Science & Technology Park]] in [[Doha]], [[Qatar]].\n\n==History==\nIncorporated in December 2008, GBI started production and deployment of the \u2018Gulf Ring\u2019<ref>{{cite web|date = 24 December 2010|title = Gulf Bridge International and SubCom commence marine operations for GBI Cable System|publisher = TeleTimes International|url = http://teletimesinternational.com/middleeast/1433/gulf-bridge-international-and-subcom-commence-marine-operations-for-gbi-cable-system|accessdate = 8 June 2011|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120324184141/http://teletimesinternational.com/middleeast/1433/gulf-bridge-international-and-subcom-commence-marine-operations-for-gbi-cable-system|archive-date = 24 March 2012|url-status = dead}}</ref>&nbsp;\u2013 a \"high speed, subsea cable system\" connecting the countries overlooking on Persian Gulf together and integrated into the larger GBI Cable System (GBICS) which has onward East and West links to Europe, Africa and Asia.<ref>{{cite press release|date = 23 September 2010|title = GBI and Interoute announce network extension partnership|publisher = Arabian Business Report|url = http://www.arabianbusiness.com/press-release/?pressReleaseId=42702|accessdate = 8 June 2011}}</ref> The high capacity demand from the Middle East and lack of diversity/resilience (as witnessed by the cable outages of 2008.<ref>{{cite web|date = 19 December 2008|title = Damaged cables cause internet outages for millions|publisher = The Guardian UK|url = https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2008/dec/19/undersea-cables-cut|accessdate = 8 June 2011}}</ref>) were large driving factors for the establishment of GBI.\n\n==Market Growth==\nBetween 2005 and 2010 the Middle East was the fastest growing region globally in terms of demand for bandwidth and capacity usage. This demand is forecast to double every three years over the course of the next decade, being driven by several factors:\n* Opening up of the regional telecom markets to competition which has stimulated an unprecedented increase in the use of mobile and broadband internet services.\n* Government initiatives around the Persian Gulf to lessen dependence on carbon based industries and diversify their investments to include other sectors, have increased the demand for superior levels of international connectivity from sectors such as Finance and Media.<ref>{{cite press release|date = 31 October 2010|title = Non-oil growth in the GCC forecasted to grow 5.1% in the next ten years|publisher = Qatar Financial Center|url = http://www.qfc.com.qa/en-us/Media-center/Media-news-detail.aspx?sNewsID=7242454d-a71a-45d4-9cf1-68e315583025|accessdate = 8 June 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Present==\nSince its establishment, the business has been validated, both by the participation of new regional investors and telecom operators looking for a new business model; and the infrastructure to enable them to provide new applications and services.<ref>{{cite press release|date = 25 May 2011|title = Gulf Bridge International (GBI) Selects Centina Systems as Their End-to-End OSS Solution Provider for Their Sub-Sea Broadband Carrier Network to Provide Outstanding Customer Service|publisher = Yahoo Finance|url = https://finance.yahoo.com/news/Gulf-Bridge-International-GBI-iw-2449996314.html?x=0&.v=1|accessdate = 8 June 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|date = 28 November 2011|title = Subsea cable network to upgrade Iraq links|publisher = Reuters|url = https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/11/28/subsea-qatar-idUSL5E7MS30H20111128| work=Reuters|accessdate = 28 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nGBI currently has presence in:\n* [[Qatar]]<ref>{{cite press release|date = 20 March 2011|title = Gulf Bridge International and Vodafone Qatar Announce Successful Cable Landing|publisher = Business Wire|url = http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20110320005036/en/Gulf-Bridge-International-Vodafone-Qatar-Announce-Successful|accessdate = 8 June 2011}}</ref>\n* [[United Arab Emirates]]<ref>{{cite press release| title = Gulf Bridge International completes its first cable landing in UAE| date = 15 March 2011| url = https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/03/14/idUS228205+14-Mar-2011+BW20110314| work=Reuters}}</ref> - Dubai and Fujairah\n* [[Iran]]<ref>{{cite web|date = 27 April 2010|title = TIC, Gulf Bridge International Agree to land GBI's submarine cable in Iran|publisher = Al Bawaba|url = http://www1.albawaba.com/business/tic-gulf-bridge-international-agree-land-gbis-submarine-cable-iran|accessdate = 8 June 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Iraq]] - This was a major first by GBI, as it placed the first ever submarine cable connecting Iraq to the world.<ref>\n{{cite web\n|date = 17 January 2012\n|title = GBI lands first subsea cable in Iraq \n|publisher = Trade Arabia\n|url = http://www.tradearabia.com/news/IT_211116.html\n|accessdate = 31 January 2012\n}}</ref>\n\n* [[Kuwait]]<ref>{{cite web\n|year = 2010\n|title = Kuwait National Technology Enterprises Ongoing Projects\n|publisher = Kuwait National Technology Enterprises\n|url = http://www.ntec.com.kw/Client/content.aspx\n|accessdate = 8 June 2011\n}}{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=June 2011}}\n* [[Bahrain]]<ref>{{cite press release\n|date = 7 March 2010\n|title = Gulf Bridge International (GBI) signs with to Batelco to Land GBI\u2019s Sub-Sea Cable System in the Kingdom of Bahrain\n|publisher = Bloomberg\n|url = https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=conewsstory&tkr=BATELCO:BI&sid=aYuIAjqoKDIY\n|accessdate = 8 June 2011\n}}</ref>\n* [[Oman]]<ref>\n{{cite press release\n| date = 10 May 2010\n| title = Gulf Bridge International, Omantel sign agreement to land GBI\u2019s sub-sea cable system in Oman\n| publisher = Submarine Telecoms Forum\n| url = http://www.subtelforum.com/articles/?p=2416\n| accessdate = 8 June 2011\n}}</ref>\n\n* [[Saudi Arabia]]<ref>\n{{cite press release\n| title = Gulf Bridge International (GBI) and the Saudi Telecom Company (STC) Announce the Landing of GBI's Submarine Cable in the East Coast of the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia.\n| date = 28 February 2010\n| url = https://www.reuters.com/article/2010/02/28/idUS56319+28-Feb-2010+BW20100228\n| work=Reuters\n}}</ref>\n* [[Italy]]<ref>\n{{cite press release\n|date = 15 November 2010\n|title = GBI and Tinet Partner Together to Extend GBI's Middle East and Asian Connectivity Into Europe and to Offer Tinet's Global IP and Ethernet Services in the Gulf Area\n|publisher = Market Wire\n|url = http://www.marketwire.com/press-release/gbi-tinet-partner-together-extend-gbis-middle-east-asian-connectivity-into-europe-offer-1353021.htm\n|accessdate = 8 June 2011\n}}</ref>- Milan\n* [[India]]<ref>\n{{cite web\n|date = 25 May 2010\n|title = Sify Technologies in pact with Gulf Bridge International\n|publisher = The Times Of India\n|url = http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2010-05-25/news/27609820_1_gulf-bridge-international-managing-director-raju-vegesna-enterprise-and-consumer-internet\n|accessdate = 8 June 2011\n}}</ref>-[[Mumbai]] and [[Chennai]]\n*[[Singapore]]\n*[[London|England-London]]\n*[[Marseille|France -Marseille]] and Paris\n*Germany-[[Frankfurt]]\n*Netherlands- [[Amsterdam]]\n\n==Products==\nGBI products include a full suite of wholesale transmission, IP capacity options, and Enterprise Services including:\n\nWDM and Transmission capacity services:\n\n* [[Synchronous Digital Hierarchy]];  IPLC Products  STM1 to STM64\n\n* [[Wavelength-division multiplexing]] ; Wavelengths at 10Gbps and 100Gbps\n\n* [[Ethernet]] over SDH;  EPL Products from 100[[Megabyte|Mbps]] to 10[[Gbps]]\t\t\n\nPacket-based IP/MPLS services:\n\n* [[Internet transit|IP Transit]]; At Neutral [[Gulf Cooperation Council|GCC]] Datacenters, [[Europe]] and [[Singapore]] from 100Mbps to 10Gbps\n* Content-Transit ; To specific desired content from 1Gbps to 10Gbps\n\n* [[Ethernet]] Over [[Multiprotocol Label Switching|MPLS]]; Backbone services across Neutral Datacenters in GCC , Europe and Singapore from 100MB to 10Gbps\n\nManaged Connectivity Services:\n\n* Global [[Virtual private network|VPNs]]; From 1[[Mbps]] global corporate [[Wide area network|WAN]] Layer 2 and 3 services over [[Multiprotocol Label Switching|MPLS]] or [[SD-WAN]] technologies\n* Cloud-Connect; From 10[[Mbps]] global Private and Public cloud connectivity ([[Amazon Web Services|AWS]], [[Microsoft Azure|Azure]], Oracle, [[SAP SE|SAP]], etc.) over [[Multiprotocol Label Switching|MPLS]] or [[SD-WAN]] technologies\n*IX-Connect; From 1[[Data-rate units|Gbps]] to 10[[Data-rate units|Gbps]] for remote peering at desired Internet Exchange worldwide\n*Content-Connect; From 1[[Data-rate units|Gbps]] to 100[[Data-rate units|Gbps]] to major contents in the [[Gulf Cooperation Council|GCC]] and [[Europe]].\n*Managed Hosting; For Media and Gaming industries consisting of [[Infrastructure as a service|IaaS]] or Colocation and connectivity services at [[Gulf Cooperation Council|GCC]] Neutral Datacenters.\n\nProfessional Services:\n\n*[[Cloud computing|Cloud]] Provisioning Services\n\n*[[Firewall (computing)|Firewall]] Assurance Management Services\n* Security and Network Consulting Services\n\n==Awards==\n* 2012 Best Niche/New Player - Capacity Europe<ref>\n{{cite web\n|date = 10 February 2013\n|title = Capacity Awards 2012\n|publisher = Capacity Magazine\n|url = http://www.capacitymagazine.com/Capacity-Awards.html\n|accessdate = 10 February 2013\n}}</ref>\n* 2012 Best Technology Investment - CommsMEA<ref>\n{{cite web\n|date = 5 December 2012\n|title = MEA telcos lauded at CommsMEA Awards\n|publisher = CommsMEA \n|url = http://www.commsmea.com/12855-mea-telcos-lauded-at-commsmea-awards/#.UReTJGdFPYM\n|accessdate = 10 February 2013\n}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.gbiinc.com/}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2011}}\n\n[[Category:Submarine communications cables in the Indian Ocean]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 2008]]\n", "name_user": "Dondervogel 2", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eProducts:I made a start correcting unit symbols perwp:mosnum; more work still needed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gulf_Bridge_International"}
{"title_page": "Doctor Who (series 8)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2015}}\n{{About|the 2014 series|the 1971 season|Doctor Who (season 8)}}\n{{Infobox television season\n| season_number        = 8\n| bgcolour             = #B8915E\n| image                = Doctor Who Series 8.jpg\n| image_upright        = 0.9\n| image_alt            = DVD cover for Series 8, featuring the Twelfth Doctor and Clara Oswald; as well as Danny Pink, Missy, a Dalek and a Cyberman.\n| caption              = DVD box set cover art\n| starring             = {{Unbulleted list|[[Peter Capaldi]]|[[Jenna Coleman]]}}\n| country              = United Kingdom\n| num_stories          = 11\n| num_episodes         = 12\n| network              = [[BBC One]]\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|2014|08|23|df=y}}\n| last_aired           = {{End date|2014|11|08|df=y}}\n| prev_series          = [[Doctor Who (2013 specials)|2013 specials]]\n| episode_list         = List of Doctor Who episodes (2005\u2013present)\n}}\nThe eighth series of the [[British television|British]] [[science fiction on television|science fiction television]] programme ''[[Doctor Who]]'' began on 23 August 2014 with \"[[Deep Breath (Doctor Who)|Deep Breath]]\" and ended with \"[[Death in Heaven]]\" on 8 November 2014. The series was officially ordered on 20 May 2013,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/news/doctor-who-renewed-season-eight-1065865.aspx|title=Doctor Who Renewed for Season 8|publisher=TV Guide|accessdate=12 November 2014}}</ref> and led by [[head writer]] and [[executive producer]] [[Steven Moffat]], alongside executive producer Brian Minchin. [[Nikki Wilson]], [[Peter Bennett (producer)|Peter Bennett]] and Paul Frift served as producers. The series is the eighth to air following the programme's revival in 2005, and is the thirty-fourth season overall. It is also the first series since [[Doctor Who (series 5)|series five]] not to be split into two parts.\n\nThe series is the first to star [[Peter Capaldi]] as the [[Twelfth Doctor]], an alien [[Time Lord]] who travels through time and space in his [[TARDIS]], which appears to be a British [[police box]] on the outside. It also stars [[Jenna Coleman]] as his [[Companion (Doctor Who)|companion]], [[Clara Oswald]]. Also playing a major recurring role in the series is [[Samuel Anderson (actor)|Samuel Anderson]] as [[Danny Pink]], Clara's boyfriend. The main story arc revolves around a mysterious woman called Missy (portrayed by [[Michelle Gomez]]), who is often seen welcoming people who have died throughout the series to the \"Promised Land\", a place that serves as an apparent afterlife to deceased characters. Missy's true identity is later revealed to be the Doctor's arch-enemy, [[Master (Doctor Who)|the Master]], who has hatched a plan using the help of the [[Cybermen]] and through manipulation of the Doctor and Clara's relationship.\n\nSteven Moffat was directly involved with the writing of seven episodes, with sole credit going to him on four, and the other three where he was credited as a \"co-writer\". Other writers who worked on this series included [[Phil Ford (writer)|Phil Ford]], [[Mark Gatiss]], [[Stephen Thompson (writer)|Stephen Thompson]], [[Gareth Roberts (writer)|Gareth Roberts]], [[Peter Harness]], [[Jamie Mathieson]] (who wrote two), and novelist [[Frank Cottrell-Boyce]]. Directors of the series included ones who had previously worked with Moffat on the show, and brand new ones. Filming began on 6 January 2014 and lasted exactly seven months, ending on 6 August 2014.\n\nThe series premiere was watched by 9.17 million viewers, the highest ratings for a premiere since [[Matt Smith (actor)|Matt Smith's]] [[The Eleventh Hour (Doctor Who)|first episode]] as the Doctor back in 2010. Ratings remained consistent throughout the course of the series, seeing a low of 6.71 million viewers with the episode \"[[Flatline (Doctor Who)|Flatline]]\", and ended with 7.60 million people watching the finale (up 150,000 viewers from the [[The Name of the Doctor|previous season finale]]). The eighth series became the highest-rated series ever in the US with an average audience of 2.04 million viewers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/01/doctor-who-clocks-highest-rated-season-yet-on-bbc-america-1201341383/|title='Doctor Who' Clocks Highest-Rated Season Yet On BBC America|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=5 January 2015|accessdate=8 December 2018}}</ref> It also received high acclaim from critics, with praise going to the writing, directing, and acting.\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==Episodes==\n{{See also|List of Doctor Who episodes (2005\u2013present)}}\nThe first episode of the series, \"[[Deep Breath (Doctor Who)|Deep Breath]]\", has a running time of 76 minutes, making it the second longest episode since the return of ''Doctor Who'' in 2005, the longest being \"[[The Day of the Doctor]]\" with a running time of 77 minutes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p023w9fy|title=Deep Breath |website= Doctor Who|publisher =[[BBC One]] |accessdate= 24 August 2014}}</ref> As with the previous series, Series 8 consists mainly of standalone episodes; the series finale was the first two-part story since \"[[The Rebel Flesh]]\" / \"[[The Almost People]]\" from the midpoint of [[Doctor Who (series 6)|Series 6]] in 2011.\n<onlyinclude>\n{{Episode table\n|background = #B8915E\n|overall = 6 |series = 6 |title = 20 |director = 14 |writer = 23 |airdate = 16 |viewers = 9 |aux4 = 6 |country = UK\n|overallT   = Story\n|seriesT    = Episode\n|aux4T      = [[Appreciation Index|{{abbr|AI|Appreciation Index|style=color:black}}]]\n|aux4R      = <ref name=\"AllRatings\" />\n|viewersR   = <ref name=\"AllRatings\" />\n|episodes   =\n{{Episode list/sublist|Doctor Who (series 8)\n |EpisodeNumber=242\n |EpisodeNumber2=1\n |Title =[[Deep Breath (Doctor Who)|Deep Breath]]\n |DirectedBy=[[Ben Wheatley]]\n |WrittenBy=[[Steven Moffat]]\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2014|08|23|df=y}}\n |Viewers=9.17\n |Aux4=82\n |ShortSummary=In [[Victorian era|Victorian]] London, a dinosaur spits out the [[TARDIS]] onto the banks of the [[River Thames]]. The newly-[[Regeneration (Doctor Who)|regenerated]] [[Twelfth Doctor]], and [[Clara Oswald|Clara]], emerge from the TARDIS. The Doctor rests at the [[Paternoster Gang]]'s residence to recover. After the [[Spontaneous human combustion|spontaneous combustion]] of the dinosaur, the Doctor and Clara take on the case of the dinosaur's death and similar recent human combustions. The Doctor and Clara are called to a restaurant, only to find it is part of a spaceship that crashed in the past and is filled with humanoid robots. Upon Clara's prompting, the robots' cyborg control node, the Half-Face Man, reveals that he is trying to reach the \"promised land\" and killed the dinosaur to use her as parts for his computer. The Doctor confronts the Half-Face Man, claiming the Half-Face Man does not want to continue his existence because of how many times his body was replaced. The Half-Face Man falls to his death from an hot-air balloon, and the other robots go lifeless. Unsure about continuing to travel with the new Doctor, Clara is convinced by a phone call from the [[Eleventh Doctor]]. Meanwhile, the Half-Face Man awakes in the promised land, greeted by a woman called Missy.\n |LineColor=B8915E\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Doctor Who (series 8)\n |EpisodeNumber=243\n |EpisodeNumber2=2\n |Title=[[Into the Dalek]]\n |DirectedBy=Ben Wheatley\n |WrittenBy=[[Phil Ford (writer)|Phil Ford]] & Steven Moffat\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2014|08|30|df=y}}\n |Viewers=7.29\n |Aux4=84\n |ShortSummary=Clara asks fellow [[Coal Hill School]] teacher and former soldier [[Danny Pink]] out for a drink. The Doctor brings Clara to the human rebel ship ''Aristotle'' to help the \"good\" [[Dalek]] Rusty, despite the Doctor's contention that Daleks cannot be turned good. The Doctor, Clara, and a team of rebels from the ''Aristotle'' are miniaturised and sent into Rusty. The Doctor repairs Rusty's power cell, but it reverts to its old way of thinking and forgets the memory of seeing the beauty of a star being born that had made it want to destroy the other Daleks. It sends a message to the Dalek mothership, giving the other Daleks the rebel ship's location. Clara awakens Rusty's memory of seeing the star being born. In an attempt to show Rusty the beauty of the universe, the Doctor connects his mind with Rusty's. Rusty, however, sees the Doctor's hatred for the Daleks, and decides to exterminate its own race. The Doctor turns down the surviving soldier Journey's offer to travel with him.\n |LineColor=B8915E\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Doctor Who (series 8)\n |EpisodeNumber=244\n |EpisodeNumber2=3\n |Title=[[Robot of Sherwood]]\n |DirectedBy=Paul Murphy\n |WrittenBy=[[Mark Gatiss]]\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2014|09|06|df=y}}\n |Viewers=7.28\n |Aux4=82\n |ShortSummary=The Doctor and Clara meet the outlaw [[Robin Hood]] in [[Sherwood Forest]]. The Doctor wins a duel against Robin by knocking him into a river. Robin takes part in an archery contest against the [[Sheriff of Nottingham]]. The Doctor challenges Robin before blowing up the target. The Doctor allows the Sheriff's robot knights to capture him, Robin and Clara so he can learn more about the Sheriff's plans. The Doctor and Clara discover the Sheriff has been trying to repair a crashed spaceship and intends to repair its circuitry with the countryside's gold, so that he can take over the world. However, there is not enough gold to make orbit, and the damage to the engines would destroy half of England. Robin defeats the Sheriff in a duel by knocking him into a gold vat. Since Robin's arm is injured (and the Doctor cheated during the archery contest), the Doctor, Clara, and Robin work together to fire the golden arrow from the contest into the ship, which then climbs into orbit where it detonates harmlessly. The Doctor admits that Robin will be remembered as a legend rather than as a man, and finds [[Maid Marian]] for him before departing.\n |LineColor=B8915E\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Doctor Who (series 8)\n |EpisodeNumber=245\n |EpisodeNumber2=4\n |Title=[[Listen (Doctor Who)|Listen]]\n |DirectedBy=[[Douglas Mackinnon]]\n |WrittenBy=Steven Moffat\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2014|09|13|df=y}}\n |Viewers=7.01\n |Aux4=82\n |ShortSummary=After a failed date with Danny, Clara returns to her home to find the Doctor awaiting her. He seeks a creature he believes has perfected its ability to hide and is related to a childhood fear everyone has of a hand grabbing someone's leg from under the bed. Clara tries to home in on her childhood using the TARDIS' telepathic circuits, but lands at the children's home where Danny, as a boy called Rupert, grew up. The Doctor comforts Rupert from his fear when an something under his bed spread scares him. After failing to apologise to Danny on the date, Clara is beckoned back to the TARDIS by time traveller Orson Pink. Clara is taken to the [[Ultimate fate of the universe|end of the universe]] where Orson's ship was stranded and the Doctor attempts to observe the hiding creature. When something on the ship knocks the Doctor out, Clara triggers the TARDIS' departure to a barn, where she finds a crying child. Hiding beneath the bed, she realises that the child is the Doctor. When the boy gets up, Clara accidentally grabs his leg. She comforts him with the Doctor's previous advice to Rupert. Orson is returned home, and Clara and Danny reconcile.\n |LineColor=B8915E\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Doctor Who (series 8)\n |EpisodeNumber=246\n |EpisodeNumber2=5\n |Title=[[Time Heist]]\n |DirectedBy=Douglas Mackinnon\n |WrittenBy=[[Stephen Thompson (writer)|Stephen Thompson]] & Steven Moffat\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2014|09|20|df=y}}\n |Viewers=6.99\n |Aux4=84\n |ShortSummary=The TARDIS' phone rings in Clara's apartment, and the Doctor and Clara find themselves in a strange chamber suffering from memory loss along with Psi the augmented human and Saibra the mutant human. They have been recruited by the Architect to rob the Bank of Karabraxos. The quartet collect the tools required for their heist, before witnessing a mysterious alien named the Teller melt the brain of a criminal with its psychic abilities. Saibra is later caught by the Teller, and activates an atomic shredder. Psi soon follows when caught by the Teller, and Clara and the Doctor gain access to the vaults of the bank. They gain the rewards of their heist, and proceed to the Private Vault, after finding Psi and Saibra; the shredders were really teleporters. The Doctor regains his lost memories back from the Teller, revealing himself as the Architect, set up to rejoin the Teller with the only other one of its species, after the bank's director, Madame Karabraxos, regretted leaving the Teller's mate in the vault to die in a solar storm and phoned the TARDIS. The Teller frees its mate. The Doctor takes the two aliens away to live out their lives.\n |LineColor=B8915E\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Doctor Who (series 8)\n |EpisodeNumber=247\n |EpisodeNumber2=6\n |Title=[[The Caretaker (Doctor Who)|The Caretaker]]\n |DirectedBy=Paul Murphy\n |WrittenBy=[[Gareth Roberts (writer)|Gareth Roberts]] & Steven Moffat\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2014|09|27|df=y}}\n |Viewers=6.82\n |Aux4=83\n |ShortSummary=Clara is trying to maintain two separate lives: one as the Doctor's companion, and the other as a school teacher in a relationship with Danny. The Doctor goes into deep cover as the caretaker at Coal Hill. Tracking the Skovox Blitzer, one of the deadliest machines created, he plans to displace it a billion years into the future where nothing else can be harmed. Danny accidentally tampers with the Doctor's trap, and the Skovox Blitzer is only sent 74 hours into the future. The Doctor learns of Danny's relationship with Clara, and Danny about Clara's double life. The Doctor believes that Clara made an error in dating a soldier. When the Skovox Blitzer rematerialises earlier than expected, the three work together to trick it into deactivating. Danny warns Clara about the Doctor pushing her into dangerous actions. The disintegrated community support awakens in the promised land, also known as the Nethersphere, being greeted Missy's assistant Seb.\n |LineColor=B8915E\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Doctor Who (series 8)\n |EpisodeNumber=248\n |EpisodeNumber2=7\n |Title=[[Kill the Moon]]\n |DirectedBy=[[Paul Wilmshurst]]\n |WrittenBy=[[Peter Harness]]\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2014|10|04|df=y}}\n |Viewers=6.91\n |Aux4=82\n |ShortSummary=The Doctor takes Clara and her student Courtney on a trip. They arrive in 2049 on a [[Space Shuttle]] to the [[Moon]] with one hundred [[Nuclear weapon|nuclear bombs]]. Noting the Moon's higher gravity and meeting Captain Lundvik, the Doctor questions her, where he's told that her team are on a suicide mission to blow up the Moon. A sudden mass high tide had threatened humanity's existence. Miners are found entombed in spider webs. The Doctor notices from the miners' photographs that the Moon is starting to break apart. A spider-like being attacks the group. The Doctor determines that the Moon is an egg, with the creature inside ready to hatch. The Doctor abandons them, forcing Lundvik, Clara, and Courtney to decide the fate of the creature. They let Earth's population decide; people of Earth vote to destroy the creature. Clara intervenes and stops the bombs' countdown, and the Doctor rescues them from the Moon. From Earth, they watch the creature hatch and the shell disintegrate, with the creature laying a new egg as a new Moon. Clara confronts the Doctor, claiming that it was his decision to make too. She leaves the Doctor, to be comforted by Danny.\n |LineColor=B8915E\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Doctor Who (series 8)\n |EpisodeNumber=249\n |EpisodeNumber2=8\n |Title=[[Mummy on the Orient Express]]\n |DirectedBy=Paul Wilmshurst\n |WrittenBy=[[Jamie Mathieson]]\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2014|10|11|df=y}}\n |Viewers=7.11\n |Aux4=85\n |ShortSummary=Clara rejoins the Doctor for one last outing before she leaves the TARDIS and the Doctor. They arrive on a train which travels through space, which is modelled after [[Orient Express]]. The Doctor soon discovers that an elderly woman called Mrs Pitt has recently been murdered by a [[mummy]] only she could see. When other occupants die in the same way, the Doctor realises that the mummy, identified as a legendary entity called the Foretold, is invisible to all but the one about to die. Once it is seen, it kills its victim in exactly sixty-six seconds. The train's computer program, Gus, reveals to the Doctor that he has tasked him to capture the Foretold. The Doctor discovers that it is a dead soldier powered by phase-shifting technology with unfinished business. The Doctor discharges the soldier by surrendering, and the train's occupants are saved. The Doctor uses the phase-shifting technology to teleport the train's occupants to safety. After a conversation with the Doctor about whether or not he is really cold-hearted, Clara decides she is not ready to leave him yet, and they set off on further adventures together.\n |LineColor=B8915E\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Doctor Who (series 8)\n |EpisodeNumber=250\n |EpisodeNumber2=9\n |Title=[[Flatline (Doctor Who)|Flatline]]\n |DirectedBy=Douglas Mackinnon\n |WrittenBy=Jamie Mathieson\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2014|10|18|df=y}}\n |Viewers=6.71\n |Aux4=85\n |ShortSummary=Arriving in [[Bristol]], the Doctor and Clara find the TARDIS has shrunk on the outside. Clara investigates the area, encountering a young graffiti artist named Rigsy, while the Doctor stays in the TARDIS until it has shrunk down to a handheld size, theorising that something was leeching its external dimensions. The Doctor tells Clara that the thing they are facing is an alien from a universe with two dimensions which is flattening people that went missing on Rigsy's estate. The creatures, known as the Boneless, have the ability to make 3D objects 2D. Clara, Rigsy, and community service people run from the Boneless into tunnels. The Doctor creates a device that can change the dimensions of objects similarly to the Boneless. The Doctor turns on Siege Mode to prevent the TARDIS from being damaged, but leaving him without enough power to deactivate Siege Mode. The Boneless have also learned to make themselves three-dimensional, and assume guises of the people they have flattened. Clara has Rigsy tricks the creatures into restoring the TARDIS by placing the TARDIS on the other side of a fake door Rigsy painted. The Doctor uses its power to send the Boneless back into their dimension.\n |LineColor=B8915E\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Doctor Who (series 8)\n |EpisodeNumber=251\n |EpisodeNumber2=10\n |Title=[[In the Forest of the Night]]\n |DirectedBy=[[Sheree Folkson]]\n |WrittenBy=[[Frank Cottrell-Boyce]]\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2014|10|25|df=y}}\n |Viewers=6.92\n |Aux4=83\n |ShortSummary=Clara's student Maebh knocks on the TARDIS after hearing a thought from Clara to find the Doctor. The Doctor answers, and realises that a forest has grown over the world. Clara and Danny lead a group of students out into the new forest after a museum sleepover. They regroup in Trafalgar Square to recover Maebh. The Doctor realises Maebh is missing, and he and Clara set out to find her. They find Maebh. Some bug-like creatures talk through Maebh, telling them they had grown the forest and previous big forests. The Doctor believes a giant solar flare Maebh predicted in her notebook is heading towards Earth. Heading back to the TARDIS, the Doctor offers an escape route. Clara refuses to become the last of her kind, and Danny decides to stay with the students. The Doctor realises the trees have grown to protect Earth. Maebh reads off a message prepared by the other students to send a message to the world to not destroy the trees. Danny tells Clara he wants to know the truth about her travels with the Doctor, and asks her to think about it first. The solar flare passes by harmlessly and the excess trees disappear.\n |LineColor=B8915E\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Doctor Who (series 8)\n |EpisodeNumber=252a{{anchor|ep252}}\n |EpisodeNumber2=11\n |Title=[[Dark Water (Doctor Who)|Dark Water]]\n |DirectedBy=[[Rachel Talalay]]\n |WrittenBy=Steven Moffat\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2014|11|01|df=y}}\n |Viewers=7.34\n |Aux4=85\n |ShortSummary=While Clara attempts to gain the courage to tell Danny about her life with the Doctor, Danny is killed. Clara attempts to blackmail the Doctor into saving Danny. The Doctor removes her from the dream state he placed on her and uses the TARDIS' telepathic interface to find Danny. The Doctor and Clara are brought to the 3W Institute, in which skeletons are contained in a blue liquid called \"dark water\" that hides the exoskeletons that support the skeletons. In an apparent afterlife called the Nethersphere, Danny is being consoled by Seb for his death. Missy greets the Doctor and Clara. The scientist Doctor Chang explains that the dead are conscious. Meanwhile, Missy awakens the skeletons and the tanks begin to drain. Clara talks with Danny, but Danny refuses to let her be with him in death. The skeletons are revealed to be [[Cyberman|Cybermen]]. Missy tells the Doctor that dying minds are uploaded the Nethersphere\u2014a [[Time Lord]] \"hard drive\"\u2014where emotions are deleted and the mind is downloaded into Cyberman bodies. The Doctor and Missy exit and find themselves on the steps of [[St Paul's Cathedral]]. Missy reveals that she is [[The Master (Doctor Who)|the Master]].\n |LineColor=B8915E\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|Doctor Who (series 8)\n |EpisodeNumber=252b\n |EpisodeNumber2=12\n |Title=[[Death in Heaven]]\n |DirectedBy=Rachel Talalay\n |WrittenBy=Steven Moffat\n |Viewers=7.60\n |Aux4=83\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2014|11|08|df=y}}\n |ShortSummary=Cybermen detonate themselves around the British Isles, to reincarnate and transform the dead into Cybermen with clouds that rain \"Cyberpollen\". Similar events occur all over the world. Danny is one of these Cybermen, and he rescues Clara. [[UNIT]] bring the Doctor and Missy aboard a plane, where the Doctor is inducted \"President of Earth\". Missy overpowers UNIT, kills Osgood, and blows up the plane. She reveals she gave Clara the phone number to the TARDIS. The Doctor reunites with Clara and Danny in a graveyard. Danny reveals that a forthcoming rainfall will convert all living people into Cybermen. Missy arrives and gifts the Doctor with control of the Cybermen to prove he and Missy are the same. The Doctor refuses and gives control to Danny, who leads other Cybermen into exploding and stopping the rainfall. Missy claims the planet Gallifrey is in its original location. The Doctor threatens to kill Missy to prevent Clara from doing so herself. Missy is seemingly disintegrated by [[Brigadier Lethbridge-Stewart]], reanimated as a Cyberman. Clara and the Doctor bid farewell with lies to each other: Clara tells the Doctor that Danny was brought back from the Nethersphere, and the Doctor tells Clara he found Gallifrey.\n |LineColor=B8915E\n}}\n}}</onlyinclude>\n\n==Casting==\n{{See also|List of Doctor Who cast members}}\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| image1 = Peter Capaldi 2009 (cropped).jpg\n| width1 = 100\n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = \n| image2 = Jenna Coleman by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| width2 = 110\n| alt2 = \n| caption2 = \n| footer = Peter Capaldi was cast in August 2013, while Jenna Coleman announced her return in March 2013\n}}\nThe show's star since 2010, [[Matt Smith (actor)|Matt Smith]] announced in June 2013 that he would be leaving ''Doctor Who''<ref name=\"MattLeaves\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/doctorwho/articles/Matt-Smith-to-leave-Doctor-Who |title=Matt Smith announces he is to leave Doctor Who |publisher=[[British Broadcasting Corporation|BBC]] |date=1 June 2013 |accessdate=2 June 2013 }}</ref> following the 2013 Christmas episode \"[[The Time of the Doctor]]\". His replacement was announced, after several weeks of speculation,<ref name=\"speculation\"/> on a special live broadcast called ''Doctor Who Live: The Next Doctor'' on 4 August as [[Peter Capaldi]], who up to that point was best known for portraying [[Spin (public relations)|spin doctor]] [[Malcolm Tucker]] in the BBC comedy series ''[[The Thick of It]]''.<ref name=\"BBC Dr Who blog\">{{cite web|author=The Doctor Who Team|title=Peter Capaldi exclusively revealed to the nation as the Twelfth Doctor|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/doctorwho/articles/Peter-Capaldi-exclusively-revealed-to-the-nation-as-the-Twelfth-Doctor|publisher=BBC|accessdate=4 August 2013}}</ref> Capaldi had previously appeared on the show as [[Lucius Caecilius Iucundus|Caecilius]] in \"[[The Fires of Pompeii]]\".<ref name=\"BBC reveal\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-23570354|title=Peter Capaldi revealed as Doctor Who's new lead|date=4 August 2013|accessdate=4 August 2013|publisher=BBC}}</ref> He also played John Frobisher in the ''Doctor Who'' spin-off ''[[Torchwood: Children of Earth]]''.\n\nIn October 2013, actress [[Neve McIntosh]] stated in an interview that recurring characters [[Madame Vastra, Jenny Flint and Strax]] (known to fans as \"the Paternoster Gang\") were due to return in the series premiere \"Deep Breath\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.denofgeek.com/tv/doctor-who/27678/doctor-who-returning-characters-confirmed-for-series-8 |title=Doctor Who: returning characters confirmed for series 8 |last1=Mellor |first1=Louisa |date=14 October 2013 |website=Den of Geek |publisher= |accessdate=14 October 2013}}</ref> On 24 February 2014, it was announced that ''[[Gavin & Stacey]]'' actor [[Samuel Anderson (actor)|Samuel Anderson]] will join the cast as the recurring character [[Danny Pink]], a teacher and Clara's colleague at [[Coal Hill School]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.doctorwho.tv/whats-new/article/samuel-anderson-joins-doctor-who-for-peter-capaldi-s-first-series |title=SAMUEL ANDERSON JOINS DOCTOR WHO FOR PETER CAPALDI'S FIRST SERIES |date=24 February 2014 |website=Doctor Who official website |accessdate=24 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nBeyond the return of the Paternoster Gang, and the casting of Samuel Anderson, the first major guest star of the series was announced in March 2014 when it was revealed that [[Keeley Hawes]] had been cast in episode five as a character named Ms. Delphox.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-26566092 |title=Keeley Hawes to star as Doctor Who villain |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=14 March 2014 |website=BBC News |publisher= |accessdate=14 March 2014}}</ref> Subsequently, [[Tom Riley (actor)|Tom Riley]], [[Ben Miller]], [[Hermione Norris]], [[Frank Skinner]], [[Foxes (singer)|Foxes]], [[Christopher Fairbank]], [[Sanjeev Bhaskar]], and [[Chris Addison]] were cast in guest roles.<ref name=\"Mackinnon\">{{cite web |url=http://www.doctorwhotv.co.uk/series-8-filming-tunnel-vision-63664.htm |title=Series 8 Filming: Tunnel Vision |website=Doctor Who TV }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/doctorwho/articles/Tom-Riley-to-star-in-an-episode-written-by-Mark-Gatiss|title=Tom Riley to star in an episode written by Mark Gatiss|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2 April 2014 |website=BBC Doctor Who |publisher=BBC |accessdate=8 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/doctorwho/articles/Ben-Miller-to-Guest-Star-in-Doctor-Who|title=Ben Miller to Guest Star in Doctor Who|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=8 April 2014 |website=BBC Doctor Who |publisher=BBC |accessdate=8 April 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"HermionieLanzarote\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/doctorwho/articles/Hermione-Norris-to-Guest-Star-in-New-Series|title=Hermione Norris to Guest Star in New Series|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=11 May 2014 |website=BBC Doctor Who |publisher=BBC |accessdate=12 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/doctorwho/articles/Frank-Skinner-to-Appear-in-New-Series-of-Doctor-Who|title=Frank Skinner to Appear in New Series of Doctor Who|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=16 May 2014 |website=BBC Doctor Who |publisher=BBC |accessdate=16 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2014/foxes-doctor-who|title=Foxes to appear in new series of Doctor Who|date=29 May 2014 |website=Media Center |publisher=BBC |accessdate=29 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/doctorwho/articles/Sanjeev-Bhaskar-to-join-cast-of-Doctor-Who|title=Sanjeev Bhaskar to join cast of Doctor Who|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=11 July 2014 |website=BBC Doctor Who |publisher=BBC |accessdate=11 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.doctorwhotv.co.uk/chris-addison-to-guest-in-series-8-finale-65608.htm |title=Chris Addison to Guest in Series 8 Finale |date=19 August 2014 |website=Doctor Who TV |accessdate=19 August 2014 }}</ref>\n\n[[Jemma Redgrave]] and [[Ingrid Oliver]] reprised their roles of Kate Stewart and Osgood, respectively, last seen in the fiftieth anniversary special \"The Day of the Doctor\", in the two-part series final \"[[Dark Water (Doctor Who)|Dark Water]]\" / \"[[Death in Heaven]]\" featuring the return of the [[Cybermen]]. [[Michelle Gomez]] was later cast as a character named Missy, described as \"The Gatekeeper of the [[Nethersphere]]\" and was originally announced to be featured in the series finale, however, Gomez also appeared in the series' first, second, sixth, ninth and tenth episodes as part of a recurring story arc.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/doctorwho/articles/Michelle-Gomez-to-star-in-Doctor-Who|title=Michelle Gomez to star in Doctor Who|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=30 June 2014 |website=BBC Doctor Who |publisher=BBC |accessdate=30 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/whats-on/whats-on-news/doctor-who-series-8-filming-7345456|title=Doctor Who films in Cardiff city centre as the Cybermen take over|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=30 June 2014 |website=Wales Online |publisher=Wales Online |accessdate=30 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.doctorwhotv.co.uk/series-8-finale-filming-returning-characters-monster-64138.htm |title=Series 8 Finale Filming: Returning Characters & Monster |date=30 June 2014 |website=Doctor Who TV |accessdate=30 June 2014 }}</ref> In \"Dark Water\", it was revealed that Missy is in fact [[The Master (Doctor Who)|The Master]], with Gomez taking over the role from [[John Simm]].\n\n==Production==\n\n===Writing and development===\nAt [[San Diego Comic-Con International|Comic-Con 2013]], Steven Moffat said that, although much of the focus at that point remained on the 50th anniversary and Christmas specials, writing for series 8 was under way:\n{{quote|The scripts [are] coming in, we know what we're going to do and how it's going to end, and what it's building to.<ref>{{cite web|author=|title=Moffat hints at 12th Doctor, Series 8|url=http://doctorwhotv.co.uk/moffat-hints-at-12th-doctor-series-8-52004.htm|publisher=Digital Spy|date=25 July 2013|accessdate=16 August 2013}}</ref>}}\n\nIn an interview with ''[[Doctor Who Magazine]]'', Moffat likened his initial plans for the Twelfth Doctor to [[Tom Baker]]'s [[Doctor Who (season 12)|first season]], with the Doctor being tricky to deal with at the beginning, but with the benefit of familiar characters to ease through the transition; Moffat also commented on the situation of Clara having to deal with the Doctor changing.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.doctorwhotv.co.uk/moffats-12th-doctor-hints-52620.htm |title=Moffat's 12th Doctor Hints |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=21 August 2013 |website=Doctor Who TV |publisher= |accessdate=22 August 2013}}</ref> Moffat has also stated that, unlike the situation with [[Colin Baker]],<ref>Colin Baker's first appearance in ''Doctor Who'' was as Commander Maxil in the [[Doctor Who (season 20)|Season 20]] serial ''[[Arc of Infinity]]'', which was broadcast 14 months prior to his initial appearance as the [[Sixth Doctor]]</ref> reference will be made to Peter Capaldi's previous appearances in the [[Whoniverse]]:\n{{quote|I remember Russell [T Davies] told me that he had a big old plan as to why there were two Peter Capaldis in the ''Who'' universe: one in [[Pompeii]] and one in ''[[Torchwood]]''. When I cast Peter and Russell got in touch to say how pleased he was, I said, \"Okay, what was your theory and does it still work?\" and he said, \"Yes it does. Here it is...\"<ref>{{cite web|author=|title=Capaldi's Past Whoniverse Appearances Not Ignored|url=http://www.doctorwhotv.co.uk/capaldis-past-appearances-not-ignored-53407.htm|publisher=Doctor Who TV|date=28 September 2013|accessdate=2 October 2013}}</ref>}}\n\n[[File:Steven Moffat by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|150px|left|Steven Moffat said that the issue of Peter Capaldi's previous appearances would be addressed, amongst other story issues.]]\n[[Chris Chibnall]], who has written five previous episodes of ''Doctor Who'', and a few for ''Torchwood'', indicated in April 2013 that he had been approached by Moffat to contribute to Series 8.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chris Chibnall for Doctor Who Series 8?|url=http://www.kasterborous.com/2013/04/chris-chibnall-for-doctor-who-series-8/|publisher=Kasterborous.com|date=16 April 2013|accessdate=19 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130508210227/http://www.kasterborous.com/2013/04/chris-chibnall-for-doctor-who-series-8/|archive-date=8 May 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> The subsequent success of his drama series ''[[Broadchurch]]'', has led to Chibnall stating that, while still willing to write for ''Doctor Who'', his schedule may mean it not being possible for this upcoming series.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chris Chibnall Denies Matt Smith will Appear in Broadchurch|url=http://www.kasterborous.com/2013/07/chris-chibnall-denies-matt-smith-will-appear-in-broadchurch/|publisher=Kasterborous.com|date=2 July 2013|accessdate=19 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130706054440/http://www.kasterborous.com/2013/07/chris-chibnall-denies-matt-smith-will-appear-in-broadchurch/|archive-date=6 July 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[Neil Cross]], who wrote two episodes in [[Doctor Who (series 7)|Series 7]], has also stated a desire to write for Series 8.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hide's Neil Cross Back for Doctor Who Series 8?|url=http://www.kasterborous.com/2013/08/hides-neil-cross-back-for-doctor-who-series-8/|publisher=Kasterborous.com|date=18 August 2013|accessdate=19 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141105020731/http://www.kasterborous.com/2013/08/hides-neil-cross-back-for-doctor-who-series-8/|archive-date=5 November 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> Cross confirmed that he would be writing at least one episode for Series 8 in August 2013, while [[Neil Gaiman]], who contributed [[The Doctor's Wife|one episode]] to Series 6 and [[Nightmare in Silver|another episode]] to Series 7, and [[Frank Cottrell-Boyce]] also stated that they were developing scripts. However, neither were able to confirm initially whether these would be for Series 8 or a subsequent series.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://whatculture.com/tv/doctor-who-series-8-writers-line-up-starts-to-take-shape.php |title=Doctor Who: Series 8 Writers Line-Up Starts To Take Shape |last1=Cornish |first1=James T. |date=21 August 2013 |website=whatculture.com |accessdate=22 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130822054718/http://whatculture.com/tv/doctor-who-series-8-writers-line-up-starts-to-take-shape.php |archivedate=22 August 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"wheatleyboyce\">{{cite web |url=http://www.doctorwhonews.net/2013/10/director-writer-news-14102013203015.html |title=Director and writer news |last1=Weight |first1=Anthony |date=14 October 2013 |website=Doctor Who News |publisher= |accessdate=15 October 2013}}</ref> On 4 July 2014, it was confirmed Boyce would also write an episode.<ref name=\"Boyce\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2014/frank-cottrell-boyce-doctor-who |title=Award-winning children's novelist and screenwriter Frank CottrellB-oyce confirmed as Doctor Who writer |website=BBC Media Centre }}</ref>\n\n[[Gareth Roberts (writer)|Gareth Roberts]], who has written five previous episodes of ''Doctor Who'', has been confirmed to be returning for Series 8.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.doctorwhonews.net/2014/01/gareth-roberts-confirmed-for-series-8.html |title=Gareth Roberts confirmed for Series 8 |last1=Johnston |first1=Connor |date=3 January 2014 |website=Doctor Who News |publisher= |accessdate=4 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 January 2014, it was announced that former producers Peter Bennett (producer in 2010, who has also worked on spin-off ''Torchwood'' and former showrunner Russell T Davies' ''[[Wizards vs Aliens]]'') and Nikki Wilson (script editor and producer from 2009 to 2010) would produce the series. Will Oswald is editing Episodes 1, 2, 5 and 6.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uk.linkedin.com/pub/will-oswald/54/9a7/373?trk=pub-pbmap |archive-url=https://archive.is/20140226194046/http://uk.linkedin.com/pub/will-oswald/54/9a7/373?trk=pub-pbmap |url-status=dead |archive-date=2014-02-26 |title=Will Oswald \u2013 United Kingdom |website=LinkedIn }}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March 2014, it was announced that [[Mark Gatiss]] will write either one or two episodes for the series. In a Q&A in [[Brazil]] he said that he believes that [[Jane Austen]] should feature in an episode, just like other famous authors who have appeared on the show, such as [[William Shakespeare]], [[Charles Dickens]], and [[Agatha Christie]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doctorwhotv.co.uk/gatiss-confirms-two-capaldi-eps-hints-at-jane-austen-story-62036.htm |title=Gatiss Confirms Two Capaldi Eps, Hints at Jane Austen Story |date=27 March 2014 |website=Doctor Who TV }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2014, it was announced [[Peter Harness]] and Jamie Mathieson would be writing for the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doctorwhotv.co.uk/two-new-writers-for-series-8-62929.htm |title=Two New Writers for Series 8 |date=30 April 2014 |website=Doctor Who TV }}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nIn August 2013, actress Jenna Coleman initially announced that filming was scheduled to begin in January 2014, after the broadcast of Peter Capaldi's initial appearance in the Christmas special that would contain the Doctor's [[Regeneration (Doctor Who)|regeneration]].<ref name=\"Series 8 news\">{{cite web|author=Simon Brew|title=Doctor Who series 8 news round-up|url=http://www.denofgeek.com/tv/doctor-who/26916/doctor-who-series-8-news-round-up|publisher=Den of Geek|date=16 August 2013|accessdate=16 August 2013}}</ref>\nIn late 2013, announcements were made for various directing appointments for the new series, with a total of six episodes allocated initially; in October, the first two episodes of the series were allocated to [[Ben Wheatley]], with production due to start in December 2013.<ref name=\"wheatleyboyce\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.screendaily.com/news/ben-wheatley-to-direct-doctor-who/5062452.article|title=Ben Wheatley to direct Doctor Who|last1=Wiseman|first1=Andreas|date=14 October 2013 |website=ScreenDaily |publisher= |accessdate=14 October 2013}}</ref> In November and December two further episodes were each allocated to Paul Murphy<ref name=\"ep3&6director\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cultbox.co.uk/news/headlines/8573-doctor-who-series-8-another-director-confirmed|title='Doctor Who' Series 8: Another director confirmed|last1=Martin|first1=William|date=27 November 2013 |website=Cultbox |publisher= |accessdate=27 November 2013}}</ref> and [[Douglas Mackinnon]].<ref name=\"DouglasMackinnonDirector\">{{cite web |url=http://www.doctorwhotv.co.uk/douglas-mackinnon-directing-series-8-56823.htm|title='Douglas Mackinnon Directing Series 8|date=14 December 2013 |website=Doctor Who TV|publisher= |accessdate=14 December 2013}}</ref> The first read through took place on 17 December 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.doctorwhotv.co.uk/peter-capaldi-readies-for-series-8-56921.htm|title=Peter Capaldi Readies for Series 8|date=17 December 2013 |website=Doctor Who TV|publisher= |accessdate=17 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nFilming began on 6 January 2014 in Cardiff,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doctorwhotv.co.uk/series-8-filming-a-paternoster-peek-57672.htm |title=Series 8 Filming: A Paternoster Peek |date=7 January 2014 |website=Doctor Who TV }}</ref> with Peter Capaldi and Jenna Coleman shooting their first scenes for Series 8 on 7 January 2014.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/doctorwho/articles/Peter-Capaldi-begins-filming-on-Doctor-Who |title=Doctor Who \u2013 Peter Capaldi begins filming on Doctor Who |date=7 January 2014 |website=BBC \u2013 Blogs }}</ref> On 22 February 2014 it was announced that [[Paul Wilmshurst]] would also direct an episode.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doctorwhotv.co.uk/another-new-director-for-series-8-61182.htm |title=Another new Director for Series 8 |date=22 February 2014 |website=Doctor Who TV }}</ref> On 11 May 2014, it was announced that an episode directed by Wilmshurst and written by Harness would be filming in [[Lanzarote]], the second time ''Doctor Who'' has filmed there after the 1984 serial ''[[Planet of Fire]]''.<ref name=\"HermionieLanzarote\"/> Filming took place in Volc\u00e1n del Cuervo, also known as the Raven\u2019s Volcano.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.doctorwhotv.co.uk/series-8-filming-volcano-day-63212.htm |title=Series 8 Filming: Volcano Day |date=13 May 2014 |website=Doctor Who TV |accessdate=13 May 2014 }}</ref> On 14 May 2014 it was announced that [[United States|American]] director [[Rachel Talalay]] would be directing two episodes of the eighth series.<ref name=\"doctorwho_rachel\">{{cite web|title=Rachel Talalay Directing Series 8|url=http://www.doctorwhotv.co.uk/rachel-talalay-directing-series-8-63233.htm|publisher=Doctor Who TV|accessdate=14 May 2014}}</ref> On 2 July 2014 filming for the finale took place at the Box Cemetery in [[Llanelli]], previously the location for the final scenes of the seventh series mid-season finale \"[[The Angels Take Manhattan]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.doctorwhotv.co.uk/series-8-finale-filming-beyond-the-grave-64171.htm |title=Series 8 Finale Filming: Beyond the Grave |date=2 July 2014 |website=Doctor Who TV |accessdate=10 July 2014 }}</ref> On 4 July 2014 it was announced that [[Sheree Folkson]] would direct an episode.<ref name=\"Boyce\" /> On 19 July 2014 filming with the Cybermen took place outside [[St Paul's Cathedral]] in [[London]], which had previously been the setting of 1968's ''[[The Invasion (Doctor Who)|The Invasion]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.doctorwhotv.co.uk/cybermen-invade-london-again-64634.htm |title=Cybermen Invade London (Again!) |date=19 July 2014 |website=Doctor Who TV }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/doctor-who-cybermen-unmasked-filming-3890551 |title=Doctor Who: Cybermen unmasked while filming legendary scenes at St Paul's Cathedral |author=Danny Walker |date=21 July 2014 |website=[[Daily Mirror]] |accessdate=23 July 2014 }}</ref>\n\nFilming on the series was completed on 6 August 2014.<ref>{{cite web|author=William Martin |url=http://www.cultbox.co.uk/news/headlines/doctor-who-series-8-has-finished-filming |title='Doctor Who' Series 8 has finished filming |publisher=CultBox |date=2014-08-08 |accessdate=2014-08-23}}</ref>\n\nProduction blocks were arranged as follows:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%; margin-right:0;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:8%\" | Block !! Episode(s) !! Director !! Writer(s) !! Producer\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | 1\n| \"[[Deep Breath (Doctor Who)|Deep Breath]]\"\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Ben Wheatley]]\n| [[Steven Moffat]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Nikki Wilson]]\n|-\n| \"[[Into the Dalek]]\"\n| [[Phil Ford (writer)|Phil Ford]] & Steven Moffat\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | 2\n| \"[[Listen (Doctor Who)|Listen]]\"\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Douglas Mackinnon]]\n| Steven Moffat\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Peter Bennett (producer)|Peter Bennett]]\n|-\n| \"[[Time Heist]]\"\n| [[Stephen Thompson (writer)|Stephen Thompson]] & Steven Moffat\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | 3\n| \"[[Robot of Sherwood]]\"\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Paul Murphy\n| [[Mark Gatiss]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Nikki Wilson\n|-\n| \"[[The Caretaker (Doctor Who)|The Caretaker]]\"\n| [[Gareth Roberts (writer)|Gareth Roberts]] & Steven Moffat\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | 4\n| \"[[Kill the Moon]]\"\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Paul Wilmshurst]]\n| [[Peter Harness]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Peter Bennett\n|-\n| \"[[Mummy on the Orient Express]]\"\n| [[Jamie Mathieson]]\n|-\n! 5\n| \"[[Flatline (Doctor Who)|Flatline]]\"\n| Douglas Mackinnon\n| Jamie Mathieson\n| Nikki Wilson\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | 6\n| \"[[Dark Water (Doctor Who)|Dark Water]]\"\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Rachel Talalay]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Steven Moffat\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Peter Bennett\n|-\n| \"[[Death in Heaven]]\"\n|-\n! 7\n| \"[[In the Forest of the Night]]\"\n| [[Sheree Folkson]]\n| [[Frank Cottrell-Boyce]]\n| Paul Frift\n|}\n\n===Design changes===\n[[File:Doctor Who title 2014.png|thumb|The redesigned ''Doctor Who'' [[title card]] for series 8.]]\nThe introduction of a new lead actor brought about another change to the title sequence. The sequence for Series 8 was inspired by a fan-made sequence produced by Billy Hanshaw, an illustrator and 3D animator from [[Leeds]], who posted it on [[YouTube]]. This eventually came to the attention of Steven Moffat, who subsequently based the official sequence on Hanshaw's work.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2014/aug/15/doctor-who-title-sequence-fan-video-steven-moffat |title=New Doctor Who title sequence inspired by viral fan creation |author=Ben Beaumont-Thomas |date=15 August 2014 |website=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=15 August 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.doctorwhotv.co.uk/the-series-8-title-sequence-65250.htm |title=The Series 8 Title Sequence |date=15 August 2014 |website=Doctor Who TV |accessdate=15 August 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media |people=Billy Hanshaw |year=2013 |title=Doctor Who original concept Peter Capaldi intro |medium=Video |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oXOBHnWiinY |accessdate=15 August 2014 |publisher=[[YouTube]]}}</ref><ref name=ibtimes-intro8>{{cite web|last1=Poladian|first1=Charles|title='Doctor Who' Season 8: Meet Billy Hanshaw, Whose Title Sequence Steven Moffat Loved So Much He Used It|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/doctor-who-season-8-meet-billy-hanshaw-whose-title-sequence-steven-moffat-loved-so-much-he-1668548|accessdate=25 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nAs director of the first block, [[Ben Wheatley]] was able to make lasting modifications to the TARDIS set. Wheatley had the cinematographer change the central column from green to golden, and had the art department create a replica of [[Tommy Westphall]]'s snowglobe from ''[[St. Elsewhere]]'', which Wheatley placed in the TARDIS set as a reference to the theory that all television exists in a shared dream reality.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/director-ben-wheatley-talks-high-rise-doctor-who-free-fire-and-more-at-tiff/|title=Director Ben Wheatley Talks 'High-Rise', 'Doctor Who', 'Free Fire' and More at TIFF|last=Weintraub|first=Steve|publisher=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|date=25 September 2015|accessdate=12 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Promotion==\nOn 10 June 2014, the BBC announced a \"World Tour\" promoting Series 8 to take place between 7\u201319 August 2014 and featured Peter Capaldi, [[Jenna Coleman]] and [[Steven Moffat]]. They visited seven cities across five continents in 12 days, where they attend fan events and media interviews. The destinations were [[Cardiff]], London, [[Seoul]], [[Sydney]], [[New York City]], [[Mexico City]] and [[Rio de Janeiro]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doctorwho.tv/whats-new/article/doctor-who-the-world-tour-takes-capaldi-coleman-and-moffat-around-the-globe |title=Doctor Who World Tour To Promote Series 8 |date=10 June 2014 |website=Doctor Who TV |accessdate=10 June 2014 }}</ref> On 13 July 2014 the first full length trailer was aired on [[BBC One]], during the final half-time of the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]].<ref name=\"radiotimes\">{{cite news |url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2014-07-13/doctor-who-watch-peter-capaldi-going-into-darkness-in-the-first-full-length-series-8-trailer |title=Doctor Who: Watch Peter Capaldi going \"into darkness\" in the first full-length series 8 trailer |first=Ben |last=Dowell |date=13 July 2014 |work=[[Radio Times]] |publisher=[[Immediate Media Company]] |accessdate=13 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nLeading up to the launch of the series, four teaser trailers were released on 23 May, 27 June, 4 July and 27 July 2014.<ref name=\"bbcaugust\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p01zp3cd|title=BBC One \u2013 Doctor Who, The New Doctor Lands in August\u2026|work=BBC|accessdate=17 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CIzgoB8pXuc |title=Doctor Who Series 8 2014: Am I a good man? Trailer \u2013 BBC One |date=27 June 2014 |website=[[YouTube]] |publisher=BBC |accessdate=27 June 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.doctorwhotv.co.uk/series-8-new-trailer-64242.htm |title=Series 8: New Teaser Trailer \"I see into your soul, Doctor\" |date=4 July 2014 |website=Doctor Who TV |accessdate=4 July 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p023lcbh |title=Doctor Who, Series 8 Teaser: Listen\u2026 |date=26 July 2014 |website=BBC |accessdate=27 July 2014 }}</ref> On 7 August 2014 an interview with Peter Capaldi was shown on [[BBC News]], featuring clips from the second episode.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.doctorwhotv.co.uk/bbc-news-series-8-preview-featuring-new-clips-65200.htm |title=BBC News Series 8 Preview Featuring New Dalek Clips |date=7 August 2014 |website=Doctor Who TV |accessdate=7 August 2014 }}</ref> Starting on 18 August, the BBC released a series of six short teasers counting down to the series' premiere.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p025051h |title=BBC One \u2013 Doctor Who \u2013 Series 8 , 5 days to go |date=18 August 2014 |website=Doctor Who |publisher=[[BBC One]] |accessdate=23 August 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p02528jb |title=BBC One \u2013 Doctor Who \u2013 Series 8 , 4 days to go\u2026 |date=19 August 2014 |website=Doctor Who |publisher=[[BBC One]] |accessdate=23 August 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p0253xpr |title=BBC One \u2013 Doctor Who \u2013 Series 8 , 3 days to go\u2026 |date=20 August 2014 |website=Doctor Who |publisher=[[BBC One]] |accessdate=23 August 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p0253y4q |title=BBC One \u2013 Doctor Who \u2013 Series 8 , 2 days to go\u2026 |date=21 August 2014 |website=Doctor Who |publisher=[[BBC One]] |accessdate=23 August 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p0253yhn |title=BBC One \u2013 Doctor Who \u2013 Series 8 Begins Tomorrow! |date=22 August 2014 |website=Doctor Who |publisher=[[BBC One]] |accessdate=23 August 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p0253ys6 |title=BBC One \u2013 Doctor Who \u2013 Series 8 Begins Today! |date=23 August 2014 |website=Doctor Who |publisher=[[BBC One]] |accessdate=23 August 2014 }}</ref>\n\n== Episode leaks ==\nOn 6 July 2014, the scripts and rough \"pre air screeners\" for the first five episodes of the series were inadvertently leaked online from [[BBC Worldwide]]'s Latin America headquarters. The leaked scripts were immediately shared online, prompting wide coverage in the media. In a statement, BBC Worldwide asked people with access to the leaked material to keep the storylines of the five episodes secret.<ref name=\"spoilers\">{{cite web |url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2014-07-07/please-dont-share-secrets-of-doctor-who-series-8---bbc-worldwide-sorry-for-five-leaked-scripts|title=Please don't share secrets of Doctor Who series 8 \u2013 BBC Worldwide \"sorry\" for five leaked scripts|author=Ben Dowell |date=7 July 2014 |website=Radio Times |accessdate=7 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 July, the black and white, watermarked \"pre air screener\" of \"Deep Breath\" was uploaded to [[The Pirate Bay]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://torrentfreak.com/leaked-dr-who-episode-appears-on-the-pirate-bay-140714/|title=Torrent Freak: LEAKED DOCTOR WHO EPISODE APPEARS ON THE PIRATE BAY|date=12 July 2014|accessdate=|website=|publisher=|last=|first=}}</ref> The video was a rough cut of series 8's first episode, missing many visual effects, but otherwise mostly complete.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2014-07-12/peter-capaldis-first-doctor-who-episode-leaks-online-6-weeks-ahead-of-broadcast |title=Peter Capaldi's first Doctor Who episode leaks online 6 weeks ahead of broadcast |author=Jonathan Holmes |date=12 July 2014 |website=[[Radio Times]] |accessdate=12 July 2014 }}</ref> The video leak was also widely covered in the media, however the BBC confirmed the leak was from the same source as the script, and had been contained. Despite the fact that the initial version of \"[[Into the Dalek]]\" contained a glitch that made it unable to download, a workable version found its way online by the second week of August 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ibtimes.com/doctor-who-season-8-leak-episode-2-torrent-finds-it-way-pirate-bay-1656396 |title='Doctor Who' Season 8 Leak: Episode 2 Torrent Finds It Way Onto The Pirate Bay |author=Charles Poladian |date=12 August 2014 |website=[[International Business Times]] |accessdate=14 August 2014 }}</ref>\n\n\"[[Robot of Sherwood]]\" was subsequently leaked in the third week of August, with fears that the rough cuts of the next three episodes, which were also included in the exposed file, would also be made available through file sharing sites.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.combom.co.uk/2014/08/doctor-who-series-8-leak-update.html?m=1 |title=Doctor Who Series 8 Leak Update: Episodes 2 and 3 Now Available |date=16 August 2014 |website=Life, Doctor Who, and Combom |accessdate=17 August 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://doctorwhoworldwide.com/2014/08/18/series-8-episode-3-leaks-online-to-file-sharing-networks/ |title=Series 8 Episode 3 Leaks Online to File Sharing Networks |date=18 August 2014 |website=Doctor Who Worldwide |accessdate=18 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006082820/http://doctorwhoworldwide.com/2014/08/18/series-8-episode-3-leaks-online-to-file-sharing-networks/ |archivedate=6 October 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> \"[[Listen (Doctor Who)|Listen]]\" and \"[[Time Heist]]\" were also leaked later on.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.combom.co.uk/2014/08/doctor-who-series-8-leak-update-episode_23.html|title=Torrent Freak: Doctor Who Series 8 Leak Update: Episode 4 Listen Now Available|date=23 August 2014|accessdate=23 August 2014 |website=Combom |publisher=|last=|first=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.combom.co.uk/2014/08/doctor-who-series-8-leak-update-episode.html|title=Torrent Freak: Doctor Who Series 8 Leak Update: Episode 5 Time Heist (But NOT Ep 4) Now Available |date=21 August 2014|accessdate=23 August 2014 |website=Combom |publisher=|last=|first=}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n===Broadcast===\nSeries 8 was initially slated to be broadcast starting in the late summer of 2014, with Steven Moffat acknowledging this likelihood in July 2013, prior to the announcement of Peter Capaldi's casting.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.doctorwhotv.co.uk/moffat-on-12th-doctor-50th-series-8-51360.htm|title=Moffat on the 12th Doctor, 50th Length, Series 8 Airdate|last1= |first1=|last2= |first2=|date=11 July 2013 |website=Doctor Who TV|publisher= |accessdate=4 September 2013}}</ref> In September however it was suggested that the broadcast date would likely be pushed back to the third quarter of 2014, which would tie in with the production starting in January 2014 and typically lasting up to 9 months before the transmission of the first episode. It was also suggested that the series would be a twelve rather than thirteen episode run.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.doctorwhotv.co.uk/series-8-for-autumn-2014-52931.htm|title=Series 8 for Autumn 2014|last1= |first1=|last2= |first2=|date=3 September 2013 |website=Doctor Who TV|publisher= |accessdate=4 September 2013}}</ref> In an October 2013 interview, Steven Moffat said that there will be at least 13 episodes in the series.<ref>{{cite web|last=Dalglish|first=Sean|title=Doctor Who TV Series 8 13 Episodes Confirmed|url=http://www.doctorwhotv.co.uk/series-8-at-least-13-episodes-in-2014-54632.htm}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2014, Ben Wheatley, director of the first two episodes, stated that his episodes would begin airing in the summer of 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.doctorwhotv.co.uk/summer-broadcast-for-doctor-who-series-8-60862.htm |title=Summer Broadcast for Doctor Who Series 8? |date=12 February 2014 |website=Doctor Who TV }}</ref>\n\nAt the final 50th anniversary event at the [[British Film Institute|BFI]] in December 2013, Steven Moffat confirmed that the series would contain 13 episodes and would be broadcast in the second half of 2014. He also stated that it would not be split into two parts, instead being transmitted continuously.<ref name=\"doctorwhotv.co.uk\">{{cite web|last=|first=|title=Moffat reaffirms no split for Series 8|url=http://www.doctorwhotv.co.uk/moffat-reaffirms-no-split-for-series-8-56617.htm|date=9 December 2013 |website=Doctor Who TV|publisher= |accessdate=9 December 2013}}</ref> Moffat also announced that this would be the standard broadcast format for future series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doctorwhotv.co.uk/uninterrupted-runs-for-series-8-and-beyond-57748.htm |title=Uninterrupted Runs for Series 8 and beyond |date=9 January 2014 |website=Doctor Who TV }}</ref> A teaser trailer released on 23 May 2014 revealed that the eighth series would air in August 2014.<ref name=\"bbcaugust\"/><ref name=\"Series8Teaser\">{{cite web| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p0225wyr|title=Doctor Who, Series 8 Teaser: I see into your soul, Doctor\u2026 |accessdate=2014-07-06}}</ref> An extended teaser released on 27 June 2014 showed the airdate to be 23 August 2014.<ref name=\"Title Confirmation\">{{cite web|url=http://www.doctorwhotv.co.uk/series-8-airdate-confirmed-new-trailer-image-64070.htm |title=Series 8 Airdate Confirmed, New Trailer & Image |date=27 June 2014 |website=Doctor Who TV }}</ref>\n\nThe first episode, \"Deep Breath\", had its world premiere on 7 August 2014, at the Cardiff visit on the World Tour.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.doctorwho.tv/whats-new/article/cardiff-doctor-who-world-tour-event-details-announced |title=Cardiff Doctor Who World Tour event details announced |date=4 July 2014 |website=Doctor Who}}</ref> Following additional preview screenings at other World Tour visits,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.doctorwho.tv/whats-new/article/london-doctor-who-world-tour-fan-event-confirmed |title=London Doctor Who World Tour fan event confirmed |date=17 July 2014 |website=Doctor Who |publisher=BBC |accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.doctorwho.tv/whats-new/article/dates-and-events-confirmed-for-korean-leg-of-doctor-who-the-world-tour |title=Dates and events confirmed for Korean leg of Doctor Who: The World Tour |date=14 July 2014 |website=Doctor Who |publisher=BBC |accessdate=16 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.doctorwho.tv/whats-new/article/sydney-fan-event-details-revealed-for-doctor-who-the-world-tour |title=Sydney fan event details revealed for Doctor Who: The World Tour |date=14 July 2014 |website=Doctor Who |publisher=BBC |accessdate=16 July 2014}}</ref> the story also received a worldwide cinema release at participating cinemas on 23 August 2014, the same day as its television broadcast.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doctorwho.tv/watch/cinema |title=Watch Doctor Who in the Cinema |website=Doctor Who |accessdate=25 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140727233412/http://www.doctorwho.tv/watch/cinema |archivedate=27 July 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n\"Dark Water\" and \"Death in Heaven\" received a 3D cinematic release on 15 and 16 September 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dr. Who 3D: Dark Water/Death in Heaven|url=https://celebrationcinema.com/movie/Dr.+Who+3D%3A+Dark+Water%2FDeath+in+Heaven/9-15-2015|publisher=Celebration! Cinema|accessdate=28 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160710205125/https://celebrationcinema.com/movie/Dr.+Who+3D%3A+Dark+Water%2FDeath+in+Heaven/9-15-2015|archive-date=10 July 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===International broadcast===\n[[BBC America]] in the United States aired the series the same day as the United Kingdom, and in Canada, it was aired on [[Space (Canadian TV channel)|Space (TV channel)]], the science fiction/fantasy channel. [[ABC1]] in Australia aired the series live with the UK.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbcwpressroom.com/bbc-america/press/doctor-world-tour-hits-new-york-august-14/ |title=Doctor Who World Tour Hits New York August 14 |date=10 June 2014 |website=BBC America Press Room }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://about.abc.net.au/press-releases/the-doctor-heads-down-under/ |title=The Doctor heads Down Under |date=11 June 2014 |website=ABC Press Releases }}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n{{See also|List of Doctor Who home video releases}}\nThe opening episode of the series \"Deep Breath\" was released as a standalone DVD and Blu-ray on 15 September 2014 in Region 2, 9 September 2014 in Region 1, and 10 September 2014 in Region 4.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbcshop.com/doctor-who/doctor-who-deep-breath-dvd/invt/bbcdvd3998 |title=Doctor Who: Deep Breath (DVD) |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=8 August 2014 |website=BBC Shop |publisher= |accessdate=15 August 2014}}</ref> A 5-disc DVD and Blu-ray boxset containing all 12 episodes was released 24 November 2014 in Region 2, 19 November in Region 4 and 9 December 2014 in Region 1.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.doctorwhotv.co.uk/series-8-dvd-pre-orders-open-already-58368.htm |title=Series 8 DVD Pre-orders Open Already |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=29 January 2014 |website=Doctor Who TV |publisher= |accessdate=30 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B00I3JR9SG/ref=as_li_ss_tl?ie=UTF8&camp=1634&creative=19450&creativeASIN=B00I3JR9SG&linkCode=as2&tag=dowhtv-21|title=Doctor Who \u2013 The Complete Series 8 [DVD] |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=29 January 2014 |website=Amazon.co.uk|publisher= |accessdate=30 January 2014}}</ref> The 3D edition of \"Dark Water\" and \"Death in Heaven\" will receive a 3D Blu-ray release on 22 September 2015 in Region 1.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvshowsondvd.com/news/Doctor-Dark-Water-Death-In-Heaven/21320|title=Doctor Who \u2013 Industry Gossip Gives a Date for 'Dark Water/Death In Heaven' 3D Blu-ray|work=TVShowsOnDVD.com|author=David Lambert|date=16 July 2015|accessdate=28 July 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150722121011/http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/news/Doctor-Dark-Water-Death-In-Heaven/21320|archivedate=22 July 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==== Individual releases ====\n{{#lst:List of Doctor Who home video releases|Series8}}\n\n==